<br>
You'd be correct in thinking so. In the Era of vikings, they had a group of people called Bezerkers. While they didn't morph into some giant racoon, what they'd do is come into battle heavly clothed. Once they meet with the enemy, they will begin shouting wildly, swinging their axes (used only axes) in all different directions while removing parts of armor/clothing. Eventually, once all clothes (typically left their pants on.. thankfully.. but only typically) they would start self mutilation and cause injury to themselves in front of the enemy. What this did was phyic out the enemy. From the standered soldier back then (british, saxon, ect) the common attitude twords battle was either offensive with some defense, defense with some offense or a veriaty between the two. They always assumed that no one would ever completly give up defense, even if it was just in the back of their mind (they would, at least, try to dodge or jump or duck). The bezerkers could, and would, give up complete defense for complete offense (which is why they only used axes. They are not made well for parrying or such, and all the weight/impact was put on one end meaning you'll have to be very offensive with the weapon and would always need to keep it in motion). The tactic worked (for the most part) untill they invented a weapon designed againts it.. but that's another store.<br>
<br>
But yeah. IF they were to follow history as it was written and be as real as possible, zerkers would not have a zerk ability, but would always considered to be zerked. They don't wish to keep to a strict real-life scene though, which allows us to have so much more to work with (how else can we get elfs, lurikeens, ect? <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ) <p>&quot;We will never be what Mythic promised we would when DAoC started, we might as well adapt or delete.&quot; -Avandor<br>
