<br>
It was a polearm with a pointy tip, a heavy flat surface on the left side, a hook on the right and a row of spikes around the base of the flat surface.<br>
<br>
Yes, it was a brutal weapon <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  It worked well because while a bezerker was so mindless in his strikes, leaving himself vulnerable, you could also keep him from getting in close where his axes can actually do something. Only an elite-like force could use the weapon, not only because of its tremendious size and weight, but the phyic-out ability that zerkers used had to be nullified by a very iron will and no real care for ones health, which not many people had back then. Guess they were the british version of suicidal maniacs. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
An interesting note on bows an archers; No one liked them back then <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  They were not considered a very strong force, and were very poorly equiped and trained. Only people who wanted to be an archer and showed interest in it were recruited. They never really proved effective out in the field (which is why no one ever really considered them as a real part of an army) because a common and easy done tactic to avoiding arrows was holding your shield above your head. The armor was also very hard to peirce and without proper trainning, they could never hit any un-plated areas (Even chain was effective against arrow fire). It was later that they finally gave archery some thought, and not only did it become something extremly usefull, but a lot of inventions stem from the idea of a bow and arrow.<br>
<br>
