The idea of Camelot we are given (full of damsels in distress and shiny chivalrous plate armour) was set totally in the wrong time zone from anyhting it could have been. The reason we assume it was set in the chivalrous years (if tehy ever existed) was beacause of the ideals of the era in which the folktales became popular and, probably, were doctored or re-written <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ... <br>
<br>
I can't recall the exact time (I'm no History buff, I'm an English student) , but it was after the French invasion of England when all the people with influence in Britain were the French nobles (which is why all the words to do with fine food, luxury, entertainment seem to be of French origin). It was here that the ideas of chivaly and courtly love (meaning devotion to a a lady's service without wanting her personally, like) caught on. You notice all the 'poncy' people liked this sort of stuff, the Victorian upper classes often had portraits made depicting themselves as chivalrous knights <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
But, yeah, in all reality King Arthur was bit more of a bastard than we think. I think they did a pretty good job mixing the two extremes of shining chivalry and caveman brutality in &quot;EXCALIBUR&quot;, myself <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
But Sam Neil was good in &quot;MERLIN&quot;, too-<br>
