<br>
Also, Tatsu, my respect for you is pretty great.  Not up their with Blame(dangit you're cool Blame), but pretty high.  So if my following statement seems insulting or arrogant foolishness, I apoligize greatly.<br>
<br>
I discovered I was 1/4 Norwegian when I was 9 when my grandmother started doing all this pointless research on geneology(old people are stupid...).  I'd always liked Vikings in particular since my favorite color was purple back then and I thought the Minnesota Vikings were just plain cool.  So I started checking out Norse Mythology books and Norse Culture books from the library.  I was a pretty big reader when I was young too...wait I'm still young...anywho...I really liked the theme of the pillaging, nun-raping viking jarl-dude.  I also was interested in the idea of a berserk.<br>
<br>
From my reading(I've read a lot on the subject),  Berserkers went into battle either naked or wearing loose garments made of bear-hide.  The word berserk is branched off of a similiar word in the Scandinavian tongue which means bear-shirt.  Hence the name berserker, bear-hide clothing.<br>
<br>
Berserkers didn't use just axes.  While the axe was a popular weapon among vikings and such, the sword was considered greatest of all weapons.  Jarls always wielded swords because the sword was a noble weapon and was thought of very highly.  Spears were also very popular because Odin, All-Father and Leader of the Aesir, wielded Grungnir, a spear which would always return to its wielder's hand, similiar to Mjollnir, Thor's weapon.  Axes were used only slightly more than the spear because spears weren't quite as adept at...pillaging should I say?  Anywho, though the berserker wasn't distinctly a very noble person, they used swords and axes quite evenly.  While berserkers did sometimes mutilate themselves in battle, it wasn't*always*willingly.  The berserkers threw themselves into a psychotic rage by sometimes consuming narcotic berries and mushrooms that were commonly found in northern Europe.  Berserkers threw themselves into rage by sheer determination to kill and plunder and rape(They missed they're ritalin that morning).  Sometimes they would become so enraged they swung their weapon so hard they wouldn't keep track of where it was going and injure themselves.  Hence them usually missing ears, fingers and toes.  This unbridaled fury and bloodlust unnerved the defenders greatly.  It's also commonly said berserkers were unreliable and dangerous infantry mainly because they would strike out fellow comrades-in-arms and would fall dead after the battle was done.  Berserkers did sometimes lose control and injure a fellow soldier and the reason some berserkers died after the battles calmed down was because they overdosed on the consumation of the mushrooms and berries so forth their systems gave up the fight after the muscles calmed down.<br>
<br>
One site I found a few months ago was a translate version of a recorded saga from a Rosetta Stone-like object unearthed from a temple.<br>
It was something along the lines of:'The man sat at the jarl's shoulder only at only the lord's request.  He was a great bear of a man, shirtless and scarred.  Bristly black hair sprouted from his head, he reaked of bear fat and grease.  His eyes were gigantic, sunken pits of darkness.  Glazed and angry were they.  He had a bristling beard from which food and twigs were entiwined.  He ate with fervor, smacking loudly and spewing remnants of the meat across the long table.  He drank seemingly dozens of horns of mead, all in one labored gulp.  The jarl himself did not know the man's name but for the man speaking near unintelligably, usually communicating with hand gestures and body language.'<br>
<br>
The scholar who translated it believed the scripture referred to a berserker who was seated at the jarl's table only because the jarl was impressed at his battle prowess.  The man was uncivalized and grotesque but was a battle-worthy opponent.  Hence the probability the man was a zerker.<br>
<br>
Anywho, that's all I can remember off the top of my head from my off-and-on research that has spanned about 3 and a half years now(I'm 13 at the moment.)<br>
<br>
