I do know that axes were perfered over swords for bezerkers. You see, a sword can be used both defensivly (parry) and offensivly (slash). With an axe, you have 75% wood, rest a big block of sharp, heavy metal. You're not likly to parry with it. This makes it ideal for the zerker because he is ALL about offensive. Vikings and not-zerkers did use all kinds of weapons besides swords and axes, but zerker did stick to axes or similer weapons (An axe that had two heads on each side for instance). I'm sure there was more then a few who used swords, but you gotta admit, would you think a man going naked with a sword is scarier than a man going naked with an axe? You know that axe is going to be swingin, probably non-stop. With that sword, he's going to deflect (or try) your attack in some fashion. Kind of puts a damper on the &quot;I'm going to go completely offensive on you&quot; trick. I'd also believe since an axe makes you full offensive, it would be even more wanted by the zerker, to help keep him from thinking of parrying that blow. It had to take some effert to put aside every peice of defense, i'd imagine.<br>
<br>
When I said heavly clothed, bear-skins were included. It was viewed as the more you took off, the more fightening they were. Of course, they didn't wear a mediocre amount of clothing. Just enough to get their point across.<br>
